Getting started with iOS configuration profiles



**This guide still needs to be completed or updated for iMazing 3. An update will be available soon**


  1. ‌Requirements

    This guide requires a supervised iPhone, iPad, or iPod touch and a licensed copy of iMazing installed on your computer.


    No supervised device? Head to How to Supervise iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch The following video quickly covers iMazing's supervision features: https://youtu.be/hkzFX1s1Cdo

  2. ‌Profiles in iMazing

    Connect your supervised device to iMazing and scroll down the datasets list to find the Profiles icon:


    1. ‌Device Profiles

      Click on the profiles icon, and iMazing will show a list of profiles currently installed on the device:


      In the bottom toolbar, click on Install from Library.


    2. ‌Profile Library

      iMazing now displays its profile library, where you can pick one or more profiles to install:


      Your profile library will be empty at first. To create a new configuration profile, click the + button.


  3. ‌Your first configuration profile

    When you create or edit a profile in the profile library, iMazing automatically launches the profile editor in a new window with the "General" section of the sidebar selected.


    1. ‌General Section


      The two most important fields here are:


      1. Pick a descriptive profile name since that's what you'll see in iMazing's profile library.

      2. The "Prevent users from removing this profile" checkbox prevents users from removing the installed profile from their iOS device's Settings app.


    2. ‌Adding a preference group

      Below the General section in the sidebar, you'll find a whole set of preference groups. To configure a profile's settings, you must add a preference group to the profile to configure its settings.


      Let's add the Restrictions preference group:

      1. Select the Restrictions item in the sidebar

      2. Click the Add Configuration Payload button in the main view



        Configuration Payload is the technical term for a preference group. A single profile can contain multiple preference groups or just one; it's up to you to organize your profiles how you see fit.


        Once added to the profile, the preference group jumps to the top of the sidebar, and the main view displays all the settings of the preference group:


    3. ‌Searching for a specific setting

      Many preference groups are available, each containing potentially hundreds of settings. Fortunately, our profile editor features deep search: type in the search box, and iMazing will show only matching preference groups as well as highlight matching settings in yellow:

  4. ‌Most useful iOS preference groups

    There are nearly 40 different preference groups available. We'll focus on the seven most useful for small businesses

    â€“ none require advanced IT skills.


    1. ‌Restrictions


      The Restrictions preference group is one of the largest. You'll find settings to turn off many device features: block the Camera, Siri, Airdrop, allowlist or denylist apps, and much more. Here are a few significant restrictions worth knowing about:


      ‌Allow modifying passcode


      Default value: true

      Turn off this option to ensure the user cannot change the passcode.


      ‌Allow modifying Wallpaper


      Default value: true

      Turn off to ensure that your company-branded wallpapers are permanently set.


      ‌Allow host pairing


      Default value: true

      Disabling host pairing means that the device won't be able to connect to unauthorized computers. The computer that supervised the device is, by default, authorized. Import the supervising organization in iMazing running on other computers to authorize them.


      âš  This setting is also available when supervising a device. If you turned off host pairing at supervision time, you cannot re-enable it via a profile.

      ‌Force encrypted backups


      Default value: false

      Enable this option; local backups will fail until the user has enabled backup encryption.


    2. ‌Web Content Filter



      This preference group is straightforward: adding it will activate Apple's built-in iOS Adult web content filter. You can additionally add allowed URLs to guarantee access and ban additional URLs.


    3. ‌Passcode Policy


      Use this preference group to guarantee a minimum of security. In the example above, we've configured the following policies:


      • Require passcode (the user must set a passcode)

      • Don't Allow simple passcode (the user cannot pick nonsecure passcodes like 1234 or 1111)

      • Minimum passcode length of 6 characters


      There are more complex rules to play with, too, such as requiring complex characters or enforcing a regular passcode change.


    4. ‌Wi-Fi Configuration


      This preference group configures access to a Wi-Fi network. There are many advanced settings there, but in most cases, you'll only have to fill out the SSID (network name) and Password fields, as in the example above.


    5. ‌Lock Screen Message


      Fill in the Lock Screen Footnote field here to add a custom message to the device's lock screen. The other fields are legacy fields for older iOS versions.


    6. ‌Web Clips

      You can add a link to any website on the device's home screen as if it were an app. Tapping the web clip 'app' will open Safari using the configured URL. Below, we're configuring a web clip pointing to iMazing's Guides page.


      ðŸ’¡ The icon must be in PNG format, with a .png file extension.


    7. ‌Single App Mode

      Single App Mode can be configured manually, but iMazing features a much more convenient direct way to put supervised devices in a supervised mode. For more info, please refer to our guide on how to put an iPhone or iPad in Single App Mode.


  5. ‌Save and install the profile

    1. ‌Saving Your Profile

      Once you've finished configuring the profile, save it (File menu, Save). Profiles you created or opened from iMazing's profile library will automatically be saved to the library, and iMazing will display a confirmation dialog. You'll get a standard Save dialog if you've opened iMazing Profile Editor directly and not from within iMazing.


    2. ‌Installing the Profile

      You can now close the profile editor and return to the profile library, where the new profile has appeared:


      Select it, click Install to install it to the target device, and see the results immediately.


    3. ‌Modifying the Profile

      You can quickly change the profile and re-install it:


      1. Click on Install from Library again

      2. In the profile library, double-click the profile you wish to edit

      3. Make your changes in the profile editor and save

      4. Install the edited profile from the library

      5. iMazing will display an overwrite prompt; confirm.


        This tight integration between the profile editor, the library, and device profiles will let you quickly test configurations and find the proper settings for your business.


  6. ‌Non-supervised devices

Configuration profiles can also be used on devices that haven't been supervised but in a much more restricted manner:


  1. After iMazing uploads the profile to the device, it must be installed manually in the Settings app.

  2. The device's passcode is required.

  3. The profile is always removable by the user.

  4. All supervised-only settings are ignored.
